              <td bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><div align="left"><font color="#000000" size="2" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">These days there are now many companies on the  market selling and calming that they sell soundproofing windows. However all is  not what it seems. Soundproofing windows are very different from conventional  windows and doors. Everything about a normal window is wrong when it comes to  how it can be effective against noise.<br>
                    <br>
The fundamental problems from normal windows are the frame, glass, seals,  locking mechanism and hardware. Normal windows will use plain glass and use  quiet small thicknesses. These don't help at all as when glass is very thin  noise resonates within it. This actually means that the noise is in-fact  conductive and not very suitable at stopping noise.<br>
The frames used in normal windows are that of aluminum which again is a  conductive material not suitable. Then we talk about the seals and locking  mechanism. In normal windows the seals will just touch the frame and not really  seal and the locking mechanism will not be tight this results in massive amount  of noise escaping though the gaps. And before you say, added foam strips does  not really help this.<br>
<br>
One of the things that we have come to find out from other windows on the  market is that funny enough these windows all display the characteristics of  ether normal windows with some modification of thermal insulated windows. It seems  from our perspective that window companies have attempted to widen their  business models by advertising that they sell soundproofing windows when in  fact they aren't really authentic soundproofing windows.<br>
